// Basic queries
db.tasks.find()                                    // All documents
db.tasks.find({ status: "todo" })                  // Filter by field
db.tasks.find({ priority: "high" }, { title: 1, status: 1, _id: 0 })  // Projection
db.tasks.findOne({ status: "completed" })          // Return single document

// Query with comparison operators
db.tasks.find({
  dueDate: { $lte: new Date("2026-04-15") },
  status: { $in: ["todo", "in-progress"] }
})

// Query nested fields and arrays
db.tasks.find({ "assignee.name": "Alex Rivera" })
db.tasks.find({ tags: "infrastructure" })  // Matches docs where array contains value

// Count, sort, paginate
db.tasks.countDocuments({ status: "todo" })
db.tasks.find({ status: "todo" })
  .sort({ dueDate: 1, priority: -1 })
  .skip(0)
  .limit(10)
```

MongoDB’s query language supports a rich set of operators. The `$in`, `$nin`, `$gt`, `$lt`, `$gte`, `$lte` operators cover most comparison needs. Logical operators `$and`, `$or`, `$not`, and `$nor` combine conditions. Array operators like `$elemMatch` let you match specific conditions within array elements rather than across the full array – a distinction that matters when your array elements are subdocuments with multiple fields that must all match simultaneously.

## Step 4: Updating and Deleting Documents

MongoDB’s update operators give you surgical precision – you can modify individual fields, push to arrays, increment counters, and set values conditionally, all without reading the document into your application first. This server-side mutation model is one of MongoDB’s strongest operational advantages over key-value stores and is a core concept in any thorough mongodb tutorial.

```
// Update a single document – change status and update timestamp
db.tasks.updateOne(
  { title: "Design task schema" },
  {
    $set: {
      status: "completed",
      updatedAt: new Date()
    },
    $inc: { "metadata.actualHours": 2 }  // Increment without reading first
  }
)

// Update multiple documents – bulk status transition
db.tasks.updateMany(
  { status: "todo", dueDate: { $lt: new Date() } },
  {
    $set: {
      status: "overdue",
      updatedAt: new Date()
    },
    $push: {
      statusHistory: {
        from: "todo",
        to: "overdue",
        changedAt: new Date()
      }
    }
  }
)

// Upsert – insert if not found, update if found
db.taskCounters.updateOne(
  { _id: "daily_completed", date: new Date().toISOString().split("T")[0] },
  { $inc: { count: 1 } },
  { upsert: true }
)

// findOneAndUpdate – atomic read-modify pattern (ideal for state machines)
const task = db.tasks.findOneAndUpdate(
  { status: "todo", priority: "high" },
  {
    $set: { status: "in-progress", startedAt: new Date() },
    $push: { assignees: "worker-node-42" }
  },
  {
    returnDocument: "after",  // Return the updated document
    sort: { dueDate: 1 }      // Pick the earliest due task
  }
)

// Array update operators
db.tasks.updateOne(
  { title: "Configure Atlas cluster" },
  {
    $addToSet: { tags: "cloud" },   // Add to array only if not present
    $pull: { tags: "old-tag" }       // Remove matching elements
  }
)

// Soft delete pattern (preferred in production)
db.tasks.updateOne(
  { _id: task._id },
  { $set: { deletedAt: new Date(), deletedBy: "admin" } }
)

// Hard delete when necessary
const result = db.tasks.deleteMany({
  status: "archived",
  archivedAt: { $lt: new Date("2025-01-01") }
})
print(`Purged ${result.deletedCount} archived tasks`)
```

The soft delete pattern – setting a `deletedAt` timestamp rather than physically removing the document – is preferred in most production systems because it preserves audit trails and allows recovery from accidental deletions. Combine it with a TTL index on the `deletedAt` field to automatically purge records after your retention period expires, keeping the collection from growing unbounded.

## Step 5: Mastering the MongoDB Aggregation Pipeline

```
// Pipeline 1: Task status summary with efficiency metrics
db.tasks.aggregate([\
  // Stage 1: Filter out soft-deleted documents\
  { $match: { deletedAt: { $exists: false } } },\
\
  // Stage 2: Group by status\
  {\
    $group: {\
      _id: "$status",\
      count: { $sum: 1 },\
      avgEstimatedHours: { $avg: "$metadata.estimatedHours" },\
      avgActualHours: { $avg: "$metadata.actualHours" },\
      highPriorityCount: {\
        $sum: { $cond: [{ $eq: ["$priority", "high"] }, 1, 0] }\
      },\
      earliestDue: { $min: "$dueDate" },\
      latestDue: { $max: "$dueDate" }\
    }\
  },\
\
  // Stage 3: Add computed efficiency field\
  {\
    $addFields: {\
      efficiencyRatio: {\
        $cond: [\
          { $gt: ["$avgEstimatedHours", 0] },\
          { $divide: ["$avgActualHours", "$avgEstimatedHours"] },\
          null\
        ]\
      }\
    }\
  },\
\
  { $sort: { count: -1 } },\
\
  // Stage 4: Final projection – reshape output\
  {\
    $project: {\
      status: "$_id",\
      _id: 0,\
      count: 1,\
      highPriorityCount: 1,\
      efficiencyRatio: { $round: ["$efficiencyRatio", 2] },\
      dueDateRange: { earliest: "$earliestDue", latest: "$latestDue" }\
    }\
  }\
])

The `$facet` stage is particularly valuable for building search result pages – it runs multiple sub-pipelines simultaneously on the same input set, so you can return both paginated results and total count in a single database round trip. This pattern eliminates the dual-query overhead that makes pagination expensive in many NoSQL implementations.

## Step 6: Indexing Strategies for Performance

Indexes are where MongoDB performance is won or lost. Every query that does not use an index results in a collection scan – reading every document in the collection. For small collections this is acceptable; for collections with millions of documents it is catastrophic. Building the right indexes is one of the highest-use activities in any MongoDB project, and MongoDB 8.0’s improved background index build performance makes it easier to add indexes to large production collections without significant downtime.

```
// Single field index – most common type
db.tasks.createIndex({ status: 1 })
db.tasks.createIndex({ dueDate: 1 })

// Compound index – follow ESR rule: Equality first, Sort second, Range last
// Supports queries on: { status }, { status, priority }, { status, priority, dueDate }
db.tasks.createIndex(
  { status: 1, priority: 1, dueDate: 1 },
  { name: "status_priority_duedate" }
)

// Sparse index – only indexes documents where the field exists
db.tasks.createIndex({ deletedAt: 1 }, { sparse: true })

// TTL index – automatically deletes documents after expiration
// Purges soft-deleted tasks 90 days after deletion
db.tasks.createIndex(
  { deletedAt: 1 },
  { expireAfterSeconds: 7776000, sparse: true }
)

// Text index – full-text search with weighted fields
db.tasks.createIndex(
  { title: "text", description: "text", tags: "text" },
  {
    weights: { title: 10, tags: 5, description: 1 },
    name: "task_text_search"
  }
)

// Text search query using the index
db.tasks.find(
  { $text: { $search: "database infrastructure" } },
  { score: { $meta: "textScore" } }
).sort({ score: { $meta: "textScore" } })

// Partial index – only indexes active tasks, reducing index footprint
db.tasks.createIndex(
  { dueDate: 1, assignee: 1 },
  {
    partialFilterExpression: { status: { $in: ["todo", "in-progress"] } },
    name: "active_tasks_due_date"
  }
)

// Analyze query execution plan
db.tasks.find({ status: "todo", dueDate: { $lt: new Date("2026-05-01") } })
  .explain("executionStats")

// Monitor index usage (MongoDB 8.0 enhanced statistics)
db.tasks.aggregate([{ $indexStats: {} }])

// List all indexes
db.tasks.getIndexes()
```

**Embed when:** The related data is always read together with the parent document, the related data is not shared across multiple parents, and the embedded array will not grow without bound. Keep documents under 16 MB and embedded arrays under a few hundred elements for reliable performance.

**Reference when:** The related data is large or unbounded, the related data is shared across multiple parent documents, or you need to query the related data independently. References in MongoDB are application-level joins performed with the `$lookup` aggregation stage.

```
// Production-grade task document – applies embed vs reference principles

// users collection – normalized; referenced from tasks
{
  _id: ObjectId(),
  email: "alex@techinsider.org",
  name: "Alex Rivera",
  role: "developer",
  teams: [ObjectId("team1"), ObjectId("team2")],
  preferences: {
    timezone: "America/New_York",
    notificationChannels: ["email", "slack"]
  },
  createdAt: ISODate("2025-01-15")
}

// tasks collection – core document with strategic embedding
{
  _id: ObjectId(),
  title: "Implement vector search feature",
  description: "Add semantic search using MongoDB 8.0 vector indexes",
  status: "in-progress",
  priority: "high",

// Denormalized assignee snapshot – fast reads, no join needed
  assignee: {
    userId: ObjectId("user123"),
    name: "Alex Rivera",
    email: "alex@techinsider.org"
  },

projectId: ObjectId("project456"),  // Referenced – queried independently
  tags: ["ai", "search", "mongodb"],

// Comments embedded – bounded array, always read with task
  comments: [\
    {\
      commentId: new ObjectId(),\
      authorId: ObjectId("user789"),\
      authorName: "Jordan Kim",\
      body: "Should we use Voyage AI embeddings or a custom model?",\
      createdAt: ISODate("2026-04-01")\
    }\
  ],

// Status audit trail – capped at last 20 entries in application logic
  statusHistory: [\
    {\
      from: "todo",\
      to: "in-progress",\
      changedAt: ISODate("2026-04-02"),\
      by: ObjectId("user123")\
    }\
  ],

metadata: { estimatedHours: 8, actualHours: 3, sprint: 14, storyPoints: 5 },

// Vector embedding for semantic search (MongoDB 8.0)
  titleEmbedding: [0.023, -0.145, 0.891],  // 1024 dimensions in practice

dueDate: ISODate("2026-04-20"),
  createdAt: ISODate("2026-04-01"),
  updatedAt: ISODate("2026-04-02")
}

// Apply JSON Schema validation to enforce document structure
db.createCollection("tasks", {
  validator: {
    $jsonSchema: {
      bsonType: "object",
      required: ["title", "status", "priority", "createdAt"],
      properties: {
        title: { bsonType: "string", minLength: 1, maxLength: 500 },
        status: {
          bsonType: "string",
          enum: ["todo", "in-progress", "completed", "overdue", "archived"]
        },
        priority: {
          bsonType: "string",
          enum: ["low", "medium", "high", "critical"]
        },
        dueDate: { bsonType: ["date", "null"] },
        tags: { bsonType: "array", items: { bsonType: "string" } }
      }
    }
  },
  validationLevel: "moderate",  // Validate inserts/updates, skip existing docs
  validationAction: "error"
})
```

Schema validation with `$jsonSchema` gives you structural guarantees without sacrificing the flexibility to add fields dynamically. Use `validationLevel: "moderate"` in production to avoid breaking existing documents during schema evolution, and tighten to `"strict"` once your data is fully migrated to the new structure.

## Step 8: MongoDB Atlas – Cloud Deployment

The acquisition of Voyage AI in February 2025 was a watershed moment for MongoDB’s AI strategy. Vector search – the ability to find semantically similar documents using embedding vectors – was previously available only in MongoDB Atlas. With MongoDB 8.0, vector search indexes are now supported in Community Edition, making semantic search a first-class capability across the entire MongoDB ecosystem. This is the feature that makes the mongodb database directly relevant to every team building AI-powered applications in 2026.

Automated Embedding in Vector Search, currently in public preview, takes this further. Instead of generating embeddings in your application code and storing them manually, you configure MongoDB to automatically generate and maintain embeddings using a configured model provider – initially Voyage AI models. This dramatically simplifies the retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) pipeline for most applications by eliminating the dual-write problem that makes self-managed embedding pipelines brittle.

```
// Step 1: Create a vector search index (Atlas or Community Edition 8.0)
db.tasks.createSearchIndex({
  name: "task_vector_index",
  type: "vectorSearch",
  definition: {
    fields: [\
      {\
        type: "vector",\
        path: "titleEmbedding",\
        numDimensions: 1024,        // Voyage AI voyage-3 produces 1024-dim vectors\
        similarity: "cosine"\
      },\
      { type: "filter", path: "status" },   // Pre-filter support\
      { type: "filter", path: "priority" }\
    ]
  }
})
```

